input.content:
{
  "week": "Week 05",
  "dateRange": "3 November - 9 November",
  "topics": [
    {
      "id": "memory-fundamentals",
      "title": "Memory: Encoding, Storage, and Retrieval",
      "subtitle": "Understanding How Memory Works",
      "summary": "Exploration of memory as a system of three interrelated processes: encoding (registration), storage, and retrieval. Covers different types of memory stores and how information flows through the memory system.",
      "keyTakeaways": [
        "Memory involves three processes: encoding (transforming sensory input), storage (retaining information), and retrieval (extracting stored information).",
        "Information can be encoded acoustically (sound), visually (images), or semantically (meaning).",
        "The memory system consists of sensory memory, short-term memory (STM), and long-term memory (LTM), each with different capacities and durations."
      ],
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "What is Memory?"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Memory is a hypothetical construct denoting three distinguishable but interrelated processes that work together to manage how we encode, retain, and recall information."
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Three Core Processes of Memory",
          "items": [
            "Registration (Encoding): The transformation of sensory input (such as a sound or visual image) into a form that can be stored in memory. Involves selective attention and answers 'How are things remembered?'",
            "Storage: The operation of holding or retaining information in memory over time. Addresses 'Where are our memories kept?' and 'Is there more than one kind of memory?'",
            "Retrieval: The process by which stored information is extracted from memory when needed. Relates to 'What do we remember?' and 'Why do we forget?'"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Encoding: How Information Enters Memory"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Some information is encoded automatically without conscious awareness, such as what you had for breakfast yesterday. Other information requires attention to become encoded. There are three main ways information can be encoded:"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Types of Encoding",
          "items": [
            "Acoustic Encoding: Encoding of sound (e.g., repeating a phone number aloud)",
            "Visual Encoding: Encoding of picture images (e.g., picturing someone's face or imagining a room's layout)",
            "Semantic Encoding: Encoding of meaning (e.g., understanding 'justice' means fairness or recalling 'photosynthesis' as how plants make food)"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Storage: Three Forms of Memory"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Memory Storage Systems",
          "items": [
            "Sensory Memory: The initial stage where sensory information is briefly held for less than a second to a few seconds. Acts as a buffer for processing and attention.",
            "Short-Term Memory (STM): Holds information for 20-30 seconds with limited capacity (5-9 items). Where we actively think about or manipulate information.",
            "Long-Term Memory (LTM): Stores information for extended periods (potentially lifetime) with vast capacity. Includes knowledge, skills, and experiences."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "icon": "Info",
          "title": "Memory Capacity and Duration",
          "text": "Short-term memory has a capacity of approximately 7±2 items (Miller, 1956) and duration of 15-30 seconds. Long-term memory has potentially unlimited capacity and can last a lifetime. Chunking information can increase STM capacity, which is why hyphenated phone numbers are easier to remember."
        }
      ],
      "questions": [
        {
          "question": "Which of the three memory processes involves transforming sensory input into a storable form?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "Storage",
            "Encoding",
            "Retrieval",
            "Consolidation"
          ],
          "answer": "Encoding",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Encoding (also called registration) is the initial process that transforms sensory input like sounds or visual images into a form that can be stored in memory.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Storage": "Storage is the second process that holds or retains information after it has been encoded.",
              "Retrieval": "Retrieval is the third process that extracts information from storage when needed.",
              "Consolidation": "While consolidation is a memory-related term, it's not one of the three main processes described in the basic memory model."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "When you repeat a phone number aloud to remember it, which type of encoding are you using?",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "Semantic encoding",
            "Visual encoding",
            "Acoustic encoding",
            "Procedural encoding"
          ],
          "answer": "Acoustic encoding",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Acoustic encoding involves encoding sound. When you repeat a phone number aloud, you're processing and storing it as sound information.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Semantic encoding": "Semantic encoding deals with the meaning of information, not its sound.",
              "Visual encoding": "Visual encoding involves pictures or images, not auditory repetition.",
              "Procedural encoding": "Procedural memory relates to skills and actions, not the encoding of phone numbers."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "According to George Miller's research (1956), what is the approximate capacity of short-term memory?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "3±2 items",
            "5±2 items",
            "7±2 items",
            "9±2 items"
          ],
          "answer": "7±2 items",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Miller's famous finding is called 'the magic number 7±2,' indicating that short-term memory can hold approximately 5-9 pieces of information (digits, words, etc.).",
            "incorrect": {
              "3±2 items": "This underestimates STM capacity according to Miller's research.",
              "5±2 items": "While this overlaps with the lower range, Miller specifically identified 7±2 as the capacity.",
              "9±2 items": "This overestimates the typical STM capacity identified by Miller."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "What is the typical duration of information in short-term memory without rehearsal?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "5-10 seconds",
            "15-30 seconds",
            "45-60 seconds",
            "2-3 minutes"
          ],
          "answer": "15-30 seconds",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Research by Peterson & Peterson (1959) showed that STM duration is approximately 15-30 seconds. Information is lost from STM if not rehearsed within 18-30 seconds.",
            "incorrect": {
              "5-10 seconds": "This is too short and underestimates STM duration.",
              "45-60 seconds": "This exceeds the typical STM duration without rehearsal.",
              "2-3 minutes": "This is far too long for unrehearsed STM, though information can be maintained longer with active rehearsal."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "Which memory store acts as a buffer that briefly holds sensory information for less than a second?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "Short-term memory",
            "Long-term memory",
            "Sensory memory",
            "Working memory"
          ],
          "answer": "Sensory memory",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Sensory memory is the initial stage that briefly holds sensory information (sight, sound, etc.) for typically less than a second to a few seconds, allowing us to process and decide what to attend to.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Short-term memory": "STM holds information for 20-30 seconds, much longer than sensory memory.",
              "Long-term memory": "LTM stores information for extended periods, not just fractions of a second.",
              "Working memory": "Working memory is a more complex model of STM that actively manipulates information, not the initial sensory buffer."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "A student is trying to remember the concept that 'photosynthesis is how plants make food.' Which type of encoding is this?",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "Acoustic encoding",
            "Visual encoding",
            "Semantic encoding",
            "Sensory encoding"
          ],
          "answer": "Semantic encoding",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Semantic encoding involves encoding the meaning of information. Understanding and remembering what photosynthesis means (how plants make food) is encoding based on meaning and concepts.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Acoustic encoding": "This would involve encoding how the word 'photosynthesis' sounds, not what it means.",
              "Visual encoding": "While one might picture a plant, the question focuses on understanding the concept's meaning.",
              "Sensory encoding": "This is not a standard type of encoding in memory theory; the three main types are acoustic, visual, and semantic."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "Why are hyphenated phone numbers easier to remember than single long numbers?",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "They use visual encoding instead of acoustic",
            "They allow for chunking, increasing STM capacity",
            "They automatically transfer to LTM faster",
            "They bypass the sensory memory stage"
          ],
          "answer": "They allow for chunking, increasing STM capacity",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Chunking groups individual digits into meaningful units (chunks). Since STM capacity is measured in chunks rather than individual items, hyphenating creates fewer chunks to remember, effectively increasing what can be held in STM.",
            "incorrect": {
              "They use visual encoding instead of acoustic": "The encoding type doesn't fundamentally change with hyphenation.",
              "They automatically transfer to LTM faster": "Chunking affects STM capacity but doesn't directly speed up LTM transfer.",
              "They bypass the sensory memory stage": "All information must pass through sensory memory regardless of how it's formatted."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens to information in STM if it is NOT rehearsed within 18-30 seconds?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "It moves to sensory memory",
            "It is permanently lost due to limited duration",
            "It automatically transfers to LTM",
            "It becomes visual instead of acoustic"
          ],
          "answer": "It is permanently lost due to limited duration",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "STM has limited duration (15-30 seconds). Without rehearsal, information decays and is lost from STM within this timeframe. Rehearsal is necessary to maintain information in STM or transfer it to LTM.",
            "incorrect": {
              "It moves to sensory memory": "Information flows forward from sensory memory to STM, not backward.",
              "It automatically transfers to LTM": "Transfer to LTM requires rehearsal; unrehearsed information is lost, not transferred.",
              "It becomes visual instead of acoustic": "The encoding type doesn't change; the information simply decays and disappears."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "Which characteristic distinguishes long-term memory from short-term memory?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "LTM uses only acoustic coding",
            "LTM has potentially unlimited capacity",
            "LTM cannot store visual information",
            "LTM requires constant rehearsal"
          ],
          "answer": "LTM has potentially unlimited capacity",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "One of the key differences between LTM and STM is capacity. While STM is limited to about 7±2 items, LTM has potentially unlimited capacity and can store vast amounts of information.",
            "incorrect": {
              "LTM uses only acoustic coding": "LTM primarily uses semantic coding but can also use visual and acoustic coding.",
              "LTM cannot store visual information": "LTM can store visual information, such as remembering what your childhood home looks like.",
              "LTM requires constant rehearsal": "Once information is in LTM, it doesn't require constant rehearsal to be maintained."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "If you can remember what you had for breakfast yesterday even though you didn't try to memorize it, this demonstrates which aspect of memory?",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "Retrieval failure",
            "Automatic encoding",
            "Semantic processing",
            "Rehearsal strategies"
          ],
          "answer": "Automatic encoding",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Automatic encoding occurs when information is encoded into memory without conscious effort or intention. Daily routine events like meals are often automatically encoded without deliberate memorization attempts.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Retrieval failure": "This refers to being unable to access stored information, which is the opposite of successfully remembering breakfast.",
              "Semantic processing": "While breakfast might be encoded semantically, the key point is that it happened automatically without effort.",
              "Rehearsal strategies": "Rehearsal involves conscious repetition, but breakfast memories typically form without deliberate rehearsal."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "In which memory store is information primarily coded acoustically?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "Sensory memory",
            "Short-term memory",
            "Long-term memory",
            "Procedural memory"
          ],
          "answer": "Short-term memory",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Short-term memory primarily uses acoustic coding, as demonstrated when you repeat information in your head (like a phone number) to keep it in STM through rehearsal.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Sensory memory": "Sensory memory holds raw sensory information before significant encoding occurs.",
              "Long-term memory": "LTM primarily uses semantic (meaning-based) coding, though it can also use visual or acoustic coding.",
              "Procedural memory": "Procedural memory is a type of LTM that stores motor skills and habits, not primarily acoustic information."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "Which memory process answers the question 'Why do we forget?'",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "Encoding",
            "Storage",
            "Retrieval",
            "Consolidation"
          ],
          "answer": "Retrieval",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Retrieval is the process of extracting stored information from memory. Forgetting can occur when we cannot successfully retrieve information, even if it was properly encoded and stored.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Encoding": "Encoding addresses 'How are things remembered?' If information isn't encoded, it was never in memory to be forgotten.",
              "Storage": "Storage addresses 'Where are memories kept?' but not specifically why we can't access them.",
              "Consolidation": "While related to memory, consolidation is not one of the three main processes that explain forgetting."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "A photographer can visualize and recall the exact composition of a photo they took years ago. This is an example of:",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "Acoustic encoding in STM",
            "Visual encoding in LTM",
            "Semantic encoding in STM",
            "Procedural encoding in LTM"
          ],
          "answer": "Visual encoding in LTM",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "The photographer is recalling visual information (the photo's composition) that has been stored for years, indicating it's in long-term memory. LTM can store visual information like images and scenes.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Acoustic encoding in STM": "STM only lasts seconds to minutes, not years, and this is visual not acoustic information.",
              "Semantic encoding in STM": "Again, STM is too brief for years-old memories, and this is visual imagery not semantic meaning.",
              "Procedural encoding in LTM": "Procedural memory stores motor skills and habits, not visual images of specific scenes."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "Which statement about the capacity and duration of memory stores is correct?",
          "difficulty": "tricky",
          "options": [
            "Sensory memory has unlimited capacity but very brief duration",
            "STM has limited capacity and unlimited duration with rehearsal",
            "LTM has unlimited capacity and potentially lifetime duration",
            "All memory stores have the same capacity but different durations"
          ],
          "answer": "LTM has unlimited capacity and potentially lifetime duration",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Long-term memory is characterized by potentially unlimited capacity (can store vast amounts of information) and can maintain memories from minutes to an entire lifetime.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Sensory memory has unlimited capacity but very brief duration": "Sensory memory has limited capacity and very brief duration (less than a second).",
              "STM has limited capacity and unlimited duration with rehearsal": "While rehearsal extends STM duration, it remains fundamentally limited; unlimited duration is a characteristic of LTM.",
              "All memory stores have the same capacity but different durations": "Memory stores differ in both capacity and duration - this is false."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "If information cannot be retrieved from memory, which of the following could be possible explanations?",
          "difficulty": "tricky",
          "options": [
            "It was never properly encoded",
            "It has decayed from storage",
            "Retrieval cues are inadequate",
            "All of the above"
          ],
          "answer": "All of the above",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Forgetting (inability to retrieve) can occur at any stage: encoding (information never entered memory), storage (information decayed over time), or retrieval (information is stored but cannot be accessed with available cues).",
            "incorrect": {
              "It was never properly encoded": "While this is one possible reason, it's not the only explanation for retrieval failure.",
              "It has decayed from storage": "Decay is one theory of forgetting but doesn't account for all retrieval failures.",
              "Retrieval cues are inadequate": "This explains some forgetting (retrieval failure) but not all cases - encoding and storage failures also occur."
            }
          }
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "id": "memory-models",
      "title": "Models of Memory: MSM, WMM, and LOP",
      "subtitle": "Theoretical Frameworks for Understanding Memory",
      "summary": "Examination of three major models of memory: the Multi-Store Model (Atkinson & Shiffrin), the Working Memory Model (Baddeley & Hitch), and the Levels of Processing Model (Craik & Lockhart). Includes different types of long-term memory.",
      "keyTakeaways": [
        "The Multi-Store Model (MSM) describes memory as three separate stores: sensory register, short-term memory, and long-term memory.",
        "The Working Memory Model (WMM) views STM as an active system with multiple components: central executive, phonological loop, visuo-spatial sketchpad, and episodic buffer.",
        "The Levels of Processing Model (LOP) argues that depth of processing, rather than rehearsal, determines memory retention.",
        "Long-term memory includes episodic (personal events), semantic (facts/knowledge), and procedural (skills) memory types."
      ],
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "The Multi-Store Model (MSM)"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Richard Atkinson and Richard Shiffrin (1968) developed the Multi-Store Model by synthesizing memory research. This structural model describes memory as having three separate stores that differ in encoding, capacity, duration, and retrieval methods."
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Three Stores in the MSM",
          "items": [
            "Sensory Register: Brief storage of sensory information before attention is paid",
            "Short-Term Memory: Limited capacity (7±2 items) and duration (15-30 seconds) requiring rehearsal",
            "Long-Term Memory: Potentially unlimited capacity and duration, storing rehearsed information"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "icon": "Info",
          "title": "Serial Position Effect",
          "text": "Murdock (1962) found that items at the beginning (primacy effect - due to LTM) and end (recency effect - due to STM) of lists are recalled better than middle items, supporting the distinction between STM and LTM."
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Evidence for MSM"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "The case of patient HM provides strong evidence for MSM. After brain surgery, HM could not form new explicit long-term memories but his short-term/working memory remained functional (STM intact, old LTM intact, new LTM severely impaired). This demonstrates a clear dissociation between STM and LTM, suggesting they are separate systems."
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Types of Long-Term Memory"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Three Types of LTM",
          "items": [
            "Episodic Memory: Storage and recall of personally experienced events tied to specific times and places (autobiographical). Includes flashbulb memories of emotionally significant events. Example: Recalling your first day of university.",
            "Semantic Memory: General knowledge, facts, and concepts not tied to personal experiences. Example: Knowing that 2+2=4 or that 'cat' refers to a furry animal.",
            "Procedural Memory: Unconscious recall of skills, habits, and motor routines learned through practice (implicit memory). Example: Riding a bicycle or brushing teeth."
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "The Working Memory Model (WMM)"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Baddeley & Hitch (1974; 2000) proposed that short-term memory is not a single passive store but an active system with multiple components that manipulate and process information."
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Components of Working Memory",
          "items": [
            "Central Executive: Acts as a manager, directing attention and coordinating other subsystems with limited capacity",
            "Phonological Loop: Stores spoken words for a short time and allows rehearsal (acoustic/verbal information)",
            "Visuo-Spatial Sketchpad: Holds and manipulates visual and spatial images",
            "Episodic Buffer: Integrates information from different sources (sound, vision, long-term memory) into unified episodes"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "callout",
          "icon": "AlertCircle",
          "title": "MSM vs WMM",
          "text": "MSM views STM as a single, passive store focusing on memory structure. WMM views STM as an active system with multiple components, focusing on memory processes. WMM provides a more detailed and dynamic model of how information is actively manipulated in short-term memory."
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "The Levels of Processing Model (LOP)"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Craik and Lockhart (1972) challenged the MSM's emphasis on rehearsal, arguing that depth of processing - not rehearsal duration - determines memory retention. Deeper, semantic processing leads to better memory than shallow processing."
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "title": "Levels of Processing",
          "items": [
            "Shallow (Structural) Processing: Focusing on physical characteristics (e.g., 'Is the word in capital letters?')",
            "Intermediate (Phonemic) Processing: Focusing on sound (e.g., 'Does the word rhyme with cat?')",
            "Deep (Semantic) Processing: Focusing on meaning (e.g., 'Does the word fit: The ___ walked into the room?')"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Craik & Tulving (1975) demonstrated that words processed at a deep, semantic level were remembered much better than words processed at shallow or phonemic levels, providing strong evidence against the MSM's rehearsal-based model."
        }
      ],
      "questions": [
        {
          "question": "Who developed the Multi-Store Model of Memory in 1968?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "Baddeley & Hitch",
            "Craik & Lockhart",
            "Atkinson & Shiffrin",
            "Miller & Selfridge"
          ],
          "answer": "Atkinson & Shiffrin",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Richard Atkinson and Richard Shiffrin developed the Multi-Store Model in 1968 by synthesizing existing memory research into a structural model with three distinct stores.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Baddeley & Hitch": "They developed the Working Memory Model (1974), not the Multi-Store Model.",
              "Craik & Lockhart": "They proposed the Levels of Processing Model (1972), a different approach to memory.",
              "Miller & Selfridge": "Miller is known for the '7±2' capacity finding, but didn't develop the MSM."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "The serial position effect, where items at the beginning and end of a list are remembered better, demonstrates what about memory?",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "All items are stored in the same memory system",
            "STM and LTM are distinct systems",
            "Rehearsal is unnecessary for memory",
            "Semantic encoding is superior to acoustic"
          ],
          "answer": "STM and LTM are distinct systems",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "The primacy effect (better recall of early items) occurs because items enter LTM through rehearsal, while the recency effect (better recall of recent items) occurs because items are still in STM. This dissociation supports MSM's claim that STM and LTM are separate systems.",
            "incorrect": {
              "All items are stored in the same memory system": "The serial position effect actually shows the opposite - different positions use different memory systems.",
              "Rehearsal is unnecessary for memory": "The primacy effect specifically depends on rehearsal allowing items to enter LTM.",
              "Semantic encoding is superior to acoustic": "The serial position effect doesn't directly address encoding types."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "Patient HM, who could not form new long-term memories after brain surgery but retained normal short-term memory, provides evidence for:",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "The levels of processing theory",
            "The working memory model",
            "Separate STM and LTM systems",
            "The importance of rehearsal"
          ],
          "answer": "Separate STM and LTM systems",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "HM's case shows a clear dissociation: STM remained intact while new LTM formation was impaired. This strongly supports the Multi-Store Model's claim that STM and LTM are separate, independent systems.",
            "incorrect": {
              "The levels of processing theory": "HM's case addresses memory structures, not depth of processing.",
              "The working memory model": "While related, HM's case primarily supports the STM/LTM distinction, the foundation of MSM.",
              "The importance of rehearsal": "HM's case shows structural separation of memory systems, not specifically about rehearsal."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "Which type of long-term memory stores personally experienced events tied to specific times and places?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "Semantic memory",
            "Procedural memory",
            "Episodic memory",
            "Working memory"
          ],
          "answer": "Episodic memory",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Episodic memory stores autobiographical events with rich contextual details including 'what,' 'when,' 'where,' and associated emotions. It's a type of explicit memory that can be consciously recalled.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Semantic memory": "Semantic memory stores general knowledge and facts NOT tied to personal experiences or specific contexts.",
              "Procedural memory": "Procedural memory stores skills and motor routines, not personal events.",
              "Working memory": "Working memory is the WMM's term for active short-term processing, not a type of LTM."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "Knowing that 2+2=4 or that 'cat' refers to a furry animal is an example of which type of memory?",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "Episodic memory",
            "Procedural memory",
            "Semantic memory",
            "Sensory memory"
          ],
          "answer": "Semantic memory",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Semantic memory involves general knowledge, facts, and concepts that aren't tied to personal experiences or specific contexts. Mathematical facts and word meanings are classic examples of semantic memory.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Episodic memory": "Episodic memory is for personal events tied to specific times and places, not general facts.",
              "Procedural memory": "Procedural memory stores skills and motor routines, not factual knowledge.",
              "Sensory memory": "Sensory memory briefly holds raw sensory information for less than a second, not learned facts."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "The ability to ride a bicycle, which is recalled unconsciously through performance rather than conscious recollection, represents:",
          "difficulty": "application",
          "options": [
            "Explicit episodic memory",
            "Explicit semantic memory",
            "Implicit procedural memory",
            "Working memory"
          ],
          "answer": "Implicit procedural memory",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "Procedural memory is a type of implicit (non-declarative) memory that stores motor skills and habits learned through practice. It's expressed through performance rather than conscious recall - you 'remember' how to ride by doing it.",
            "incorrect": {
              "Explicit episodic memory": "Episodic memory is explicit but stores personal events, not motor skills.",
              "Explicit semantic memory": "Semantic memory stores facts consciously, not unconscious motor skills.",
              "Working memory": "Working memory is active short-term processing, not storage of learned skills."
            }
          }
        },
        {
          "question": "In the Working Memory Model, which component acts as a 'manager' that directs attention and coordinates other subsystems?",
          "difficulty": "learning",
          "options": [
            "Phonological loop",
            "Visuo-spatial sketchpad",
            "Central executive",
            "Episodic buffer"
          ],
          "answer": "Central executive",
          "explanation": {
            "correct": "The central executive in Baddeley & Hitch's WMM acts like a manager with limited capacity that directs attention and coordinates the other subsystems (phonological loop, visuo-spatial sketchpad, episodic buffer).",
